                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d483">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.93/303: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-22T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 22, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 22—10:07 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>115. Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs today inquired whether I knew the
                    procedure which Department of State intends to follow in bringing about change
                    in status of Legation set forth in Department’s telegram No. 36 of May 15, 7
                    p.m. He asked specifically whether the Department would ask for <hi
                        rend="italic">agrément</hi> of new appointee before nomination was made. I
                    stated that I would inquire. Can the Department give me necessary information as
                    to procedure and probable time when plan will be presented? I expect unless
                    otherwise instructed to leave Nanking for Peiping via Shanghai on the night of
                    June 3.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
